, fixing you with her wonder-struck, beautiful, myopic eyes.

“Where are your parents?” she once asked Smurov.

“In a very distant churchyard,” he answered, and for some reason made a little bow.

Evgenia, who was tossing a ping-pong ball in one hand, said she could remember their mother and Vanya could not. That evening there was no one besides Smurov and the inevitable Mukhin: Marianna had gone to a concert, Khrushchov was working in his room, and Roman Bogdanovich had stayed at home, 